# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: layer3-switching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] Portions of the network that are VLAN-aware (i.e., IEEE 802.1Q conformant) can include VLAN tags.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] When a frame enters the VLAN-aware portion of the network, a tag is added to represent the VLAN membership.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] Each frame must be distinguishable as being within exactly one VLAN.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] A frame in the VLAN-aware portion of the network that does not contain a VLAN tag is assumed to be flowing on the **native VLAN**.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] The standard was developed by IEEE 802.1, a working group of the IEEE 802 standards committee, and continues to be actively revised with notable amendments including IEEE 802.1ad, IEEE 802.1ak and IEEE 802.1s.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] The 802.1Q-2014 revision incorporated the IEEE 802.1D-2004 standard, which originally defined bridging and Spanning Tree Protocol.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] 802.1Q adds a 32-bit field between the source MAC address and the EtherType fields of the original frame.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] Under 802.1Q, the maximum frame size is extended from 1,518 bytes to 1,522 bytes.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] The minimum frame size remains 64 bytes, but a bridge may extend the minimum frame size from 64 to 68 bytes on transmission.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] This allows a tag to be popped without needing additional padding.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] Two bytes are used for the tag protocol identifier (TPID), the other two bytes for tag control information (TCI).
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] The TCI field is further divided into PCP, DEI, and VID.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] in order to identify the frame as an IEEE 802.1Q-tagged frame.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] This field is located at the same position as the EtherType field in untagged frames, and is thus used to distinguish the frame from untagged frames.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] Different PCP values can be used to prioritize different classes of traffic.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] ) May be used separately or in conjunction with PCP to indicate frames eligible to be dropped in the presence of congestion.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] A 12-bit field specifying the VLAN to which the frame belongs.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] All other values may be used as VLAN identifiers, allowing up to 4,094 VLANs.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] The VID value 0xFFF is reserved for implementation use; it must not be configured or transmitted.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] 0xFFF can be used to indicate a wildcard match in management operations or filtering database entries.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] In other words, the VLAN tag follows the SNAP header.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] For 802.3 frames in LLC-SNAP format, the order is opposite; the VLAN tag is placed *before* the LLC-SNAP header.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] Because inserting the VLAN tag changes the frame, 802.1Q encapsulation forces a recalculation of the original frame check sequence field in the Ethernet trailer.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] The IEEE 802.3ac standard increased the maximum Ethernet frame size from 1518 bytes to 1522 bytes to accommodate the four-byte VLAN tag.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] Some network devices that do not support the larger frame size will process these frames successfully but may report them as *baby giant* anomalies.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] IEEE 802.1ad introduced the concept of double tagging.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] Double tagging can be useful for Internet service providers (ISPs), allowing them to use their VLANs internally while carrying traffic from clients that is already VLAN tagged.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] The outer (next to the source MAC and representing ISP VLAN) S-TAG (service tag) comes first, followed by the inner C-TAG (customer tag).
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] In such cases, 802.1ad specifies a TPID of 0x88a8 for service-provider outer S-TAG.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] IEEE 802.1Q defines the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), an application of the Multiple Registration Protocol, allowing bridges to negotiate the set of VLANs to be used over a specific link.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] MVRP replaced the slower GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) in 2007 with the IEEE 802.1ak-2007 amendment.
[src:layer3-switching/ieee-802-1q] The 2003 revision of the standard was the first to include the Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (MSTP), which was originally defined in IEEE 802.1s.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] Networks are separated from each other by specialized hosts, called gateways or routers with specialized software support optimized for routing.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] **IP forwarding** algorithms in most routing software determine a route through a shortest path algorithm.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] In routers, packets arriving at an interface are examined for source and destination addressing and queued to the appropriate outgoing interface according to their destination address and a set of rules and performance metrics.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] Rules are encoded in a routing table that contains entries for all interfaces and their connected networks.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] If no rule satisfies the requirements for a network packet, it is forwarded to a default route.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] Routing tables are maintained either manually by a network administrator, or updated dynamically by a routing protocol.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] A routing protocol specifies how routers communicate and share information about the topology of the network, and the capabilities of each routing node.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] Different protocols are often used for different topologies or different application areas.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] For example, the Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) protocol is generally used within an enterprise and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) is used on a global scale.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] BGP is the de facto standard for worldwide Internet routing.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] Routing protocols may be broadly distinguished by their realm of operation in terms of network scope.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] Interior gateway protocols are used for routing within autonomous systems, while exterior gateway protocols route traffic between them.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] The former group is exemplified by the Routing Information Protocol (RIP) and Open Shortest Path First (OSPF), while the Exterior Gateway Protocol (EGP) and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) are examples of the exterior type.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] BGP is the dominant route distribution protocol used on the Internet.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] The IP forwarding algorithm is a specific implementation of routing for IP networks.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] In order to achieve a successful transfer of data, the algorithm uses a routing table to select a next-hop router as the next destination for a datagram.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] When multiple route table entries match, the entry with the longest subnet mask is chosen as it is the most specific one.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] If there are multiple routes with the same subnet mask, the route with the lowest metric is used.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] If there are multiple default routes, the metric is also used to determine which to use.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] If there are multiple routes with the same subnet mask and metric, the system may use equal-cost multi-path routing as a forwarding strategy.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] When no route is available, an ICMP error message is sent to the originator of the packet, to inform that host that the packet could not be delivered.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] To avoid unnecessary retransmission to avoid network congestion, the sending host should either stop transmitting or choose another address or route.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] The host has several network interfaces.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] *eth0* is the interface name of the network interface card representing an Ethernet port.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] *ppp0* is a PPPoE interface, which is configured as the default route in this example.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] A default route is recognized by the destination *0.0.0.0* and the flag *G*.
[src:layer3-switching/ip-routing] A network router is identified by the network mask *255.255.255.255* and the flag *H*.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A **multilayer switch** (**MLS**) is a computer networking device that switches on OSI layer 2 like an ordinary network switch and provides extra functions on higher OSI layers.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] The MLS was invented by engineers at Digital Equipment Corporation.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Switching technologies are crucial to network design, as they allow traffic to be sent only where it is needed in most cases, using fast, hardware-based methods.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Switching uses different kinds of network switches.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A standard switch is known as a *layer-2 switch* and is commonly found in nearly any LAN.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] *Layer-3* or *layer-4* switches require advanced technology (see managed switch) and are more expensive and thus are usually only found in larger LANs or in special network environments.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Multi-layer switching combines layer-2, -3 and -4 switching technologies and provides high-speed scalability with low latency.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Multi-layer switching can move traffic at wire speed and also provide layer-3 routing.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] There is no performance difference between forwarding at different layers because the routing and switching are all hardware-based – routing decisions are made by specialized application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) with the help of content-addressable memory.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A multilayer switch can prioritize packets by the 6 bit differentiated services code point (DSCP).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] These 6 bits were originally used for type of service.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] MLSs are also able to route IP traffic between VLANs like a common router.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] The routing is normally as quick as switching (at wire speed).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-2 switching uses the MAC addresses of the hosts’ network interface controllers (NICs) to decide where to forward frames.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-2 switching is hardware-based, which means switches use ASICs to build and maintain the forwarding information base and to perform packet forwarding at wire speed.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] One way to think of a layer-2 switch is as a multiport bridge.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-2 switching is highly efficient because there is no modification to the frame required.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Encapsulation of the packet changes only when the data packet passes through dissimilar media (such as from Ethernet to FDDI).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-2 switching is used for workgroup connectivity and network segmentation (breaking up collision domains).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] This allows a flatter network design with more network segments than conventional networks joined by repeater hubs and routers.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-2 switches have the same limitations as bridges.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Bridges break up collision domains, but the network remains one large broadcast domain which can cause performance issues and limits the size of a network.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Broadcast and multicasts, along with the slow convergence of spanning tree, can cause major problems as the network grows.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Because of these problems, layer-2 switches cannot completely replace routers.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Bridges are good if a network is designed by the 80/20 rule: users spend 80 percent of their time on their local segment.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A layer-3 switch can perform some or all of the functions normally performed by a router.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Most network switches, however, are limited to supporting a single type of physical network, typically Ethernet, whereas a router may support different kinds of physical networks on different ports.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-3 switching is solely based on the (destination) IP address stored in the header of an IP datagram (layer-4 switching may use other information in the header).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] The difference between a layer-3 switch and a router is the way the device is making the routing decision.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Conventionally, routers use microprocessors to make forwarding decisions in software, while the switch performs only hardware-based packet switching (by specialized ASICs with the help of content-addressable memory).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] However, many routers now also have advanced hardware functions to assist with forwarding.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] The main advantage of layer-3 switches is the potential for lower network latency as a packet can be routed without making extra network hops to a router.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] For example, connecting two distinct segments (e.g.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] VLANs) with a router to a standard layer-2 switch requires passing the frame to the switch (first L2 hop), then to the router (second L2 hop) where the packet inside the frame is routed (L3 hop) and then passed back to the switch (third L2 hop).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A layer-3 switch accomplishes the same task without the need for a router (and therefore additional hops) by making the routing decision itself, i.e. the packet is routed to another subnet and switched to the destination network port simultaneously.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Because many layer-3 switches offer the same functionality as conventional routers they can be used as cheaper, lower latency replacements in some networks.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] IEEE has developed hierarchical terminology that is useful in describing forwarding and switching processes.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Network devices without the capability to forward packets between subnetworks are called end systems (ESs, singular ES), whereas network devices with these capabilities are called intermediate systems (ISs).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] ISs are further divided into those that communicate only within their routing domain (intradomain IS) and those that communicate both within and between routing domains (interdomains IS).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A routing domain is generally considered as a portion of an internetwork under common administrative authority and is regulated by a particular set of administrative guidelines.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Routing domains are also called autonomous systems.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A common layer-3 capability is an awareness of IP multicast through IGMP snooping.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] With this awareness, a layer-3 switch can increase efficiency by delivering the traffic of a multicast group only to ports where the attached device has signaled that it wants to listen to that group.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-3 switches typically support IP routing between VLANs configured on the switch.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Some layer-3 switches support the routing protocols that routers use to exchange information about routes between networks.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-4 switching means hardware-based layer-3 switching technology that can also consider the type of network traffic (for example, distinguishing between UDP and TCP).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-4 switching provides additional datagram inspection by reading the port numbers found in the transport layer header to make routing decisions (i.e. ports used by HTTP, FTP and VoIP).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] These port numbers are found in RFC 1700 and reference the upper-layer protocol, program, or application.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Using layer-4 switching, the network administrator can configure a layer-4 switch to prioritize data traffic by application.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-4 information can also be used to help make routing decisions.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] For example, extended access lists can filter packets based on layer-4 port numbers.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Another example is accounting information gathered by open standards using sFlow.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A layer-4 switch can use information in the transport-layer protocols to make forwarding decisions.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Principally this refers to an ability to use source and destination port numbers in TCP and UDP communications to allow, block and prioritize communications.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Some switches can use packet information up to OSI layer 7; these may be called layer 4–7 switches, **content switches**, **content services switches**, web switches or application switches.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Content switches are typically used for load balancing among groups of servers.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Load balancing can be performed on HTTP, HTTPS, VPN, or any TCP/IP traffic using a specific port.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Load balancing often involves destination network address translation so that the client of the load-balanced service is not fully aware of which server is handling its requests.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Some layer 4–7 switches can perform Network address translation (NAT) at wire speed.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Content switches can often be used to perform standard operations such as SSL encryption and decryption to reduce the load on the servers receiving the traffic, or to centralize the management of digital certificates.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-7 switching is a technology used in a content delivery network (CDN).
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Some applications require that repeated requests from a client are directed at the same application server.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Since the client isn't generally aware of which server it spoke to earlier, content switches define a notion of stickiness.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] For example, requests from the same source IP address are directed to the same application server each time.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Stickiness can also be based on SSL IDs, and some content switches can use cookies to provide this functionality.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] The router operates on the transport layer and makes decisions on where to send the packets.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Modern load balancing routers can use different rules to make decisions on where to route traffic.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] This can be based on least load, or fastest response times, or simply balancing requests out to multiple destinations providing the same services.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] This is also a redundancy method, so if one machine is not up, the router will not send traffic to it.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] The router may also have NAT capability with port and transaction awareness and performs a form of port translation for sending incoming packets to one or more machines that are hidden behind a single IP address.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] Layer-7 switches may distribute the load based on uniform resource locators (URLs), or by using some installation-specific technique to recognize application-level transactions.
[src:layer3-switching/multilayer-switch] A layer-7 switch may include a web cache and participate in a *content-distribution network* (*CDN*).
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A **router** is a computer and networking device that forwards data packets between computer networks, including internetworks such as the global Internet.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Routers perform the *traffic directing* functions on the Internet.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A router is connected to two or more data lines from different IP networks.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] When a data packet comes in on a line, the router reads the network address information in the packet header to determine the ultimate destination.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Then, using information in its routing table or routing policy, it directs the packet to the next network on its journey.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A data packet is forwarded from one router to another through an internetwork until it reaches its destination node.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The most familiar type of IP routers are home and small office routers that forward IP packets between the home computers and the Internet.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] More sophisticated routers, such as enterprise routers, connect large business or ISP networks to powerful core routers that forward data at high speed along the optical fiber lines of the Internet backbone.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Routers can be built from standard computer parts but are mostly specialized purpose-built computers.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Early routers used software-based forwarding, running on a CPU.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] More sophisticated devices use application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) to increase performance or add advanced filtering and firewall functionality.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The concepts of a *switching node* using software and an *interface computer* were first proposed by Donald Davies in 1966 for the NPL network.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The same idea was conceived by Wesley Clark the following year for use in the ARPANET, which were named *Interface Message Processors* (IMPs).
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] These computers had fundamentally the same functionality as a router does today.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The idea for a router (called a *gateway* at the time) initially came about through an international group of computer networking researchers called the International Network Working Group (INWG).
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] These gateway devices were different from most previous packet switching schemes in two ways.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] First, they connected dissimilar kinds of networks, such as serial lines and local area networks.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Second, they were connectionless devices, which had no role in assuring that traffic was delivered reliably, leaving that function entirely to the hosts.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] This particular idea, the end-to-end principle, was contained in the work of Donald Davies.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The concept was explored in practice by various groups, with the intention to produce a working system for internetworking.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] There were three notable contemporaneous programs.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The first was an implementation directed by Louis Pouzin of the CYCLADES network, which was designed and developed during 1972-3.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The second was a program at Xerox PARC to explore new networking technologies, which produced the PARC Universal Packet system.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Some time after early 1974, the first Xerox routers became operational.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Due to corporate intellectual property concerns, it received little attention outside Xerox for years.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The third was a DARPA-initiated program, which began during 1973-4.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] This drew on the work of the other two programs, expanded significantly, and went on to create the TCP/IP architecture in use today.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] University College London (UCL) provided a gateway between British research groups and the ARPANET from 1973 until the late 1980s, latterly using SATNET.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The first true IP router was developed by Ginny Travers at BBN, as part of that DARPA-initiated effort, during 1975–1976.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] By the end of 1976, three PDP-11-based routers were in service in the experimental prototype Internet.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Mike Brecia, Ginny Travers, and Bob Hinden received the IEEE Internet Award for early IP routers in 2008.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The first multiprotocol routers were independently created by staff researchers at MIT and Stanford in 1981 and both were also based on PDP-11s.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Stanford's router program was led by William Yeager and MIT's by Noel Chiappa.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Virtually all networking now uses TCP/IP, but multiprotocol routers are still manufactured.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] They were important in the early stages of the growth of computer networking when protocols other than TCP/IP were in use.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Modern routers that handle both IPv4 and IPv6 are multiprotocol but are simpler devices than those that process AppleTalk, DECnet, IPX, and Xerox protocols.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] From the mid-1970s and in the 1980s, general-purpose minicomputers served as routers.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Modern high-speed routers are network processors or highly specialized computers with extra hardware acceleration added to speed both common routing functions, such as packet forwarding, and specialized functions such as IPsec encryption.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] There is substantial use of Linux and Unix software-based machines, running open source routing code, for research and other applications.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The Cisco IOS operating system was independently designed.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Major router operating systems, such as Junos and NX-OS, are extensively modified versions of Unix software.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] When multiple routers are used in interconnected networks, the routers can exchange information about destination addresses using a routing protocol.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Each router builds up a routing table, a list of routes, between two computer systems on the interconnected networks.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A router may have interfaces for multiple types of physical layer connections, such as copper cables, fiber optic, or wireless transmission.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] It can also support multiple network layer transmission standards.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Each network interface is used to enable data packets to be forwarded from one transmission system to another.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Routers may also be used to connect two or more logical groups of computer devices known as subnets, each with a unique network prefix.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Routers may provide connectivity within enterprises, between enterprises and the Internet, or between internet service providers' (ISPs') networks; they are also responsible for directing data between different networks.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The largest routers (such as the Cisco CRS-1 or Juniper PTX) interconnect the various ISPs, or may be used in large enterprise networks.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Smaller routers usually provide connectivity for typical home and office networks.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] All sizes of routers may be found inside enterprises.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The most powerful routers are usually found in ISPs, academic and research facilities.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Large businesses may also need more powerful routers to cope with ever-increasing demands of intranet data traffic.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A hierarchical internetworking model for interconnecting routers in large networks is in common use.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Some routers can connect to Data service units for T1 connections via serial ports.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The hierarchical internetworking model divides enterprise networks into three layers: core, distribution, and access.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Access routers, including small office/home office (SOHO) models, are located at home and customer sites such as branch offices that do not need hierarchical routing of their own.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Typically, they are optimized for low cost.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Some SOHO routers are capable of running alternative free Linux-based firmware like Tomato, OpenWrt, or DD-WRT.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Distribution routers aggregate traffic from multiple access routers.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Distribution routers are often responsible for enforcing quality of service across a wide area network (WAN), so they may have considerable memory installed, multiple WAN interface connections, and substantial onboard data processing routines.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] They may also provide connectivity to groups of file servers or other external networks.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] In enterprises, a core router may provide a collapsed backbone interconnecting the distribution tier routers from multiple buildings of a campus, or large enterprise locations.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] They tend to be optimized for high bandwidth but lack some of the features of edge routers.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] External networks must be carefully considered as part of the overall security strategy of the local network.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A router may include a firewall, VPN handling, and other security functions, or they may be handled by separate devices.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Routers also commonly perform network address translation, which restricts connections initiated from external connections but is not recognized as a security feature by all experts.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Some experts argue that open source routers are more secure and reliable than closed source routers because errors and potentially exploitable vulnerabilities are more likely to be discovered and addressed in an open-source environment.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Routers are also often distinguished on the basis of the network in which they operate.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A router in a local area network (LAN) of a single organization is called an *interior router*.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A router that is operated in the Internet backbone is described as *exterior router*.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] While a router that connects a LAN with the Internet or a wide area network (WAN) is called a *border router*, or *gateway router*.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Routers intended for ISP and major enterprise connectivity usually exchange routing information using the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Wi-Fi routers combine the functions of a router, switch and a wireless access point.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] They are typically devices with a small form factor, operating on the standard electric power supply for residential use.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Connected to the Internet as offered by an Internet service provider, they provide Internet access through Ethernet and Wi-Fi for home or office use.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The main purpose of a router is to connect multiple networks and forward packets destined either for directly attached networks or more remote networks.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A router is considered a layer-3 device because its primary forwarding decision is based on the information in the layer-3 IP packet, specifically the destination IP address.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] When a router receives a packet, it searches its routing table to find the best match between the destination IP address of the packet and one of the addresses in the routing table.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Once a match is found, the packet is encapsulated in the layer-2 data link frame for the outgoing interface indicated in the table entry.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A router typically does not look into the packet payload, but only at the layer-3 addresses to make a forwarding decision, plus optionally other information in the header for hints on, for example, quality of service (QoS).
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] For pure IP forwarding, a router is designed to minimize the state information associated with individual packets.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Once a packet is forwarded, the router does not retain any historical information about the packet.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The routing table itself can contain information derived from a variety of sources, such as a default or static routes that are configured manually, or dynamic entries from routing protocols where the router learns routes from other routers.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] A default route is one that is used to route all traffic whose destination does not otherwise appear in the routing table; it is common – even necessary – in small networks, such as a home or small business, where the default route simply sends all non-local traffic to the Internet service provider.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] The default route can be manually configured (as a static route); learned by dynamic routing protocols; or be obtained by DHCP.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Besides deciding to which interface a packet is forwarded, which is handled primarily via the routing table, a router also has to manage congestion when packets arrive at a rate higher than the router can process.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Three policies commonly used are tail drop, random early detection (RED), and weighted random early detection (WRED).
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Tail drop is the simplest and most easily implemented: the router simply drops new incoming packets once buffer space in the router is exhausted.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] RED probabilistically drops datagrams early when the queue exceeds a pre-configured portion of the buffer, until reaching a pre-determined maximum, when it drops all incoming packets, thus reverting to tail drop.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] WRED can be configured to drop packets more readily depending on the type of traffic.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Another function a router performs is traffic classification and deciding which packet should be processed first.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] This is managed through QoS, which is critical when Voice over IP is deployed, so as not to introduce excessive latency.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Yet another function a router performs is called policy-based routing, where special rules are constructed to override the rules derived from the routing table when a packet forwarding decision is made.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Some of the functions may be performed through an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) to avoid the overhead of scheduling CPU time to process the packets.
[src:layer3-switching/router-computing] Others may have to be performed through the CPU as these packets need special attention that cannot be handled by an ASIC.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] In computer networking, a **routing table**, or **routing information base** (**RIB**), is a data table stored in a router or a network host that lists the routes to particular network destinations, and in some cases, metrics (distances) associated with those routes.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] The routing table contains information about the topology of the network immediately around it.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] The construction of routing tables is the primary goal of routing protocols.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Static routes are entries that are fixed, rather than resulting from routing protocols and network topology discovery procedures.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] A routing table is analogous to a distribution map in package delivery.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Whenever a node needs to send data to another node on a network, it must first know *where* to send it.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] If the node cannot directly connect to the destination node, it has to send it via other nodes along a route to the destination node.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Each node needs to keep track of which way to deliver various packages of data, and for this, it uses a routing table.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] A routing table is a database that keeps track of paths, like a map, and uses these to determine which way to forward traffic.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] A routing table is a data file in RAM that is used to store route information about directly connected and remote networks.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Nodes can also share the contents of their routing table with other nodes.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] The primary function of a router is to forward a packet toward its destination network, which is the destination IP address of the packet.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] To do this, a router needs to search the routing information stored in its routing table.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] The routing table contains network/next hop associations.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] These associations tell a router that a particular destination can be optimally reached by sending the packet to a specific router that represents the next hop on the way to the final destination.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] The next hop association can also be the outgoing or exit interface to the final destination.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] With hop-by-hop routing, each routing table lists, for all reachable destinations, the address of the next device along the path to that destination: the next hop.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Assuming that the routing tables are consistent, the simple algorithm of relaying packets to their destination's next hop thus suffices to deliver data anywhere in a network.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Hop-by-hop is the fundamental characteristic of the IP Internet layer and the OSI Network Layer.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] When a router interface is configured with an IP address and subnet mask, the interface becomes a host on that attached network.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] A directly connected network is a network that is directly attached to one of the router interfaces.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] The network address and subnet mask of the interface, along with the interface type and number, are entered into the routing table as a directly connected network.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] A remote network is a network that can only be reached by sending the packet to another router.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Routing table entries to remote networks may be either dynamic or static.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Dynamic routes are routes to remote networks that were learned automatically by the router through a dynamic routing protocol.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Static routes are routes that a network administrator manually configured.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Routing tables are also a key aspect of certain security operations, such as unicast reverse path forwarding (uRPF).
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] In this technique, which has several variants, the router also looks up, in the routing table, the *source address* of the packet.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] If there exists no route back to the source address, the packet is assumed to be malformed or involved in a network attack and is dropped.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] The need to record routes to large numbers of devices using limited storage space represents a major challenge in routing table construction.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] On the Internet, the currently dominant address aggregation technology is a bitwise prefix matching scheme called Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR).
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Supernetworks can also be used to help control routing table size.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] *metric*: The routing metric of the path through which the packet is to be sent.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] The route will go in the direction of the gateway with the lowest metric.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] *interface*: Such as eth0 for the first Ethernet card, eth1 for the second Ethernet card, etc.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] Routing tables are generally not used directly for packet forwarding in modern router architectures; instead, they are used to generate the information for a simpler forwarding table.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] This forwarding table contains only the routes that are chosen by the routing algorithm as preferred routes for packet forwarding.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] It is often in a compressed or pre-compiled format that is optimized for hardware storage and lookup.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] This router architecture separates the control plane function of the routing table from the forwarding plane function of the forwarding table.
[src:layer3-switching/routing-table] This separation of control and forwarding provides uninterrupted high-performance forwarding.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] A **virtual local area network** (**VLAN**) is a local area network broadcast domain that is partitioned and isolated in a virtual network at the data link layer (OSI layer 2).
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] A VLAN behaves like a virtual network switch or network link that can share the same physical structure with other VLANs while staying logically separate from them.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs work by applying tags to network frames that are forwarded within the broadcast domain, creating the appearance and functionality of network traffic that behaves as if it were split between separate networks.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In this way, VLANs can keep network applications separate despite being connected to the same physical network, and without requiring multiple sets of cabling and networking devices to be deployed.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs allow network administrators to group hosts together even if the hosts are not directly connected to the same network switch.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Because VLAN membership can be configured through software, this can greatly simplify network design and deployment.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Without VLANs, grouping hosts according to their resources requires relocating nodes or rewiring data links.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs allow devices that must be kept separate to share the cabling of a physical network and yet be prevented from directly interacting with one another.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This managed sharing yields gains in simplicity, security, traffic control, and economy.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Many Internet hosting services use VLANs to separate customers' private zones from one another, enabling each customer's servers to be grouped within a single network segment regardless of where the individual servers are located in the data center.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Some precautions are needed to prevent traffic "escaping" from a given VLAN, an exploit known as VLAN hopping.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] To subdivide a network into VLANs, one configures network equipment.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Simpler equipment might partition only each physical port, in which case each VLAN runs over a dedicated network cable.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] More sophisticated devices can mark frames through VLAN tagging, so that a single interconnect (*trunk*) may be used to transport data for multiple VLANs.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Since VLANs share bandwidth, a VLAN trunk can use link aggregation, quality-of-service prioritization, or both to route data efficiently.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs address issues such as scalability, security, and network management.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Network architects set up VLANs to provide network segmentation.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Routers between VLANs filter broadcast traffic, enhance network security, perform address summarization, and mitigate network congestion.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In a network utilizing broadcasts for service discovery, address assignment and resolution and other services, as the number of peers on a network grows, the frequency of broadcasts also increases.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs can help manage broadcast traffic by forming multiple broadcast domains.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Breaking up a large network into smaller independent segments reduces the amount of broadcast traffic each network device and network segment has to bear.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Switches may not bridge network traffic between VLANs, as doing so would violate the integrity of the VLAN broadcast domain.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs can also help create multiple layer 3 networks on a single physical infrastructure.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs are data link layer (OSI layer 2) constructs, analogous to Internet Protocol (IP) subnets, which are network layer (OSI layer 3) constructs.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In an environment employing VLANs, a one-to-one relationship often exists between VLANs and IP subnets, although it is possible to have multiple subnets on one VLAN.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Without VLAN capability, users are assigned to networks based on geography and are limited by physical topologies and distances.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs can logically group networks to decouple the users' network location from their physical location.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] By using VLANs, one can control traffic patterns and react quickly to employee or equipment relocations.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs provide the flexibility to adapt to changes in network requirements and allow for simplified administration.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] A common infrastructure shared across VLAN trunks can provide a measure of security with great flexibility for a comparatively low cost.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Quality of service schemes can optimize traffic on trunk links for real-time (e.g.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] However, VLANs as a security solution should be implemented with great care as they can be defeated unless implemented carefully.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In cloud computing VLANs, IP addresses, and MAC addresses in the cloud are resources that end users can manage.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] To help mitigate security issues, placing cloud-based virtual machines on VLANs may be preferable to placing them directly on the Internet.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] After successful experiments with voice over Ethernet from 1981 to 1984, W.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] David Sincoskie joined Bellcore and began addressing the problem of scaling up Ethernet networks.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] At 10 Mbit/s, Ethernet was faster than most alternatives at the time.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] However, Ethernet was a broadcast network and there was no good way of connecting multiple Ethernet networks together.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This limited the total bandwidth of an Ethernet network to 10 Mbit/s and the maximum distance between nodes to a few hundred feet.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] By contrast, although the existing telephone network's speed for individual connections was limited to 56 kbit/s (less than one hundredth of Ethernet's speed), the total bandwidth of that network was estimated at 1 Tbit/s (100,000 times greater than Ethernet).
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Although it was possible to use IP routing to connect multiple Ethernet networks together, it was expensive and relatively slow.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Sincoskie started looking for alternatives that required less processing per packet.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In the process, he independently reinvented transparent bridging, the technique used in modern Ethernet switches.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] However, using switches to connect multiple Ethernet networks in a fault-tolerant fashion requires redundant paths through that network, which in turn requires a spanning tree configuration.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This ensures that there is only one *active* path from any source node to any destination on the network.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This causes centrally located switches to become bottlenecks, limiting scalability as more networks are interconnected.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] To help alleviate this problem, Sincoskie invented VLANs by adding a tag (an individual label, such as A, B, C, and so on) to each Ethernet frame.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In this scheme, each switch could be assigned to handle frames of a specific tag and ignore the rest.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] The networks could be interconnected with three spanning trees, one for each color.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] By sending a mix of different frame tags, the aggregate bandwidth could be improved.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Sincoskie referred to this as a *multitree bridge*.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] He and Chase Cotton created and refined the algorithms necessary to make the system feasible.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This *color* is what is now known in the Ethernet frame as the IEEE 802.1Q header, or the VLAN tag.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] While VLANs are commonly used in modern Ethernet networks, they are not used in the manner first envisioned here.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In 1998, Ethernet VLANs were described in the first edition of the IEEE 802.1Q-1998 standard.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This was extended with IEEE 802.1ad to allow nested VLAN tags in service of provider bridging.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This mechanism was improved with IEEE 802.1ah-2008.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Early network designers often segmented physical LANs with the aim of reducing the size of the Ethernet collision domain—thus improving performance.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] When Ethernet switches made this a non-issue (because each switch port is a collision domain), attention turned to reducing the size of the data link layer broadcast domain.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs were first employed to separate several broadcast domains across one physical medium.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] A VLAN can also serve to restrict access to network resources without regard to physical topology of the network.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLANs operate at the data link layer of the OSI model.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Administrators often configure a VLAN to map directly to an IP network, or subnet, which gives the appearance of involving the network layer.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Generally, VLANs within the same organization will be assigned different non-overlapping network address ranges.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] There is no issue with separate VLANs using identical overlapping address ranges (e.g. two VLANs each use the private network *192.168.0.0/16*).
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] However, it is not possible to route data between two networks with overlapping addresses without delicate IP remapping, so if the goal of VLANs is segmentation of a larger overall organizational network, non-overlapping addresses must be used in each separate VLAN.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] A basic switch that is not configured for VLANs has VLAN functionality disabled or permanently enabled with a *default VLAN* that contains all ports on the device as members.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] The default VLAN typically uses VLAN identifier 1.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Every device connected to one of its ports can send packets to any of the others.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Separating ports by VLAN groups separates their traffic very much like connecting each group using a distinct switch for each group.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Remote management of the switch requires that the administrative functions be associated with one or more of the configured VLANs.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In the context of VLANs, the term *trunk* denotes a network link carrying multiple VLANs, which are identified by labels (or *tags*) inserted into their packets.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Such trunks must run between *tagged ports* of VLAN-aware devices, so they are often switch-to-switch or switch-to-router links rather than links to hosts.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] (Note that the term 'trunk' is also used for what Cisco calls "channels" : Link Aggregation or Port Trunking).
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] A router (Layer 3 device) serves as the backbone for network traffic going across different VLANs.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] It is only when the VLAN port group is to extend to another device that tagging is used.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Since communications between ports on two different switches travel via the uplink ports of each switch involved, every VLAN containing such ports must also contain the uplink port of each switch involved, and traffic through these ports must be tagged.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Switches typically have no built-in method to indicate VLAN to port associations to someone working in a wiring closet.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] It is necessary for a technician to either have administrative access to the device to view its configuration, or for VLAN port assignment charts or diagrams to be kept next to the switches in each wiring closet.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] The protocol most commonly used today to support VLANs is IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] The IEEE 802.1 working group defined this method of multiplexing VLANs in an effort to provide multivendor VLAN support.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Prior to the introduction of the 802.1Q standard, several proprietary protocols existed, such as Cisco Inter-Switch Link (ISL) and 3Com's Virtual LAN Trunk (VLT).
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Cisco also implemented VLANs over FDDI by carrying VLAN information in an IEEE 802.10 frame header, contrary to the purpose of the IEEE 802.10 standard.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Both ISL and IEEE 802.1Q perform *explicit tagging* – the frame itself is tagged with VLAN identifiers.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] ISL uses an external tagging process that does not modify the Ethernet frame, while 802.1Q uses a frame-internal field for tagging, and therefore does modify the basic Ethernet frame structure.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This internal tagging allows IEEE 802.1Q to work on both access and trunk links using standard Ethernet hardware.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Under IEEE 802.1Q, the maximum number of VLANs on a given Ethernet network is 4,094 (4,096 values provided by the 12-bit VID field minus reserved values at each end of the range, 0 and 4,095).
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This does not impose the same limit on the number of IP subnets in such a network since a single VLAN can contain multiple IP subnets.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] IEEE 802.1ad extends the number of VLANs supported by adding support for multiple, nested VLAN tags.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] IEEE 802.1aq (Shortest Path Bridging) expands the VLAN limit to 16 million.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Both improvements have been incorporated into the IEEE 802.1Q standard.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Inter-Switch Link (ISL) is a Cisco proprietary protocol used to interconnect switches and maintain VLAN information as traffic travels between switches on trunk links.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] ISL is provided as an alternative to IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] ISL is available only on some Cisco equipment and has been deprecated.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP) is a Cisco proprietary protocol that propagates the definition of VLANs on the whole local area network.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VTP is available on most of the Cisco Catalyst Family products.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] The comparable IEEE standard in use by other manufacturers is GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) or the more recent Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP).
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol is an application of Multiple Registration Protocol that allows automatic configuration of VLAN information on network switches.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Specifically, it provides a method to dynamically share VLAN information and configure the needed VLANs.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLAN membership can be established either statically or dynamically.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Static VLANs are also referred to as port-based VLANs.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Static VLAN assignments are created by assigning ports to a VLAN.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] As a device enters the network, the device automatically assumes the VLAN of the port.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] If the user changes ports and needs access to the same VLAN, the network administrator must manually make a port-to-VLAN assignment for the new connection.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Dynamic VLANs are created using software or by protocol.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] With a VLAN Management Policy Server (VMPS), an administrator can assign switch ports to VLANs dynamically based on information such as the source MAC address of the device connected to the port or the username used to log onto that device.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] As a device enters the network, the switch queries a database for the VLAN membership of the port that device is connected to.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Protocol methods include Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP) and the somewhat obsolete GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP).
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] In a switch that supports protocol-based VLANs, traffic may be handled on the basis of its protocol.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] Essentially, this segregates or forwards traffic from a port depending on the particular protocol of that traffic; traffic of any other protocol is not forwarded on the port.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] This allows, for example, IP and IPX traffic to be automatically segregated by the network.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] VLAN cross connect (CC or VLAN-XC) is a mechanism used to create Switched VLANs, VLAN CC uses IEEE 802.1ad frames where the S Tag is used as a Label as in MPLS.
[src:layer3-switching/vlan] IEEE approves the use of such a mechanism in part 6.11 of IEEE 802.1ad-2005.
